The Durham conference</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="3" relname="solutionhood">

        What&apos;s the expression?</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="39" relname="span">  `Fool&apos;s rush in .....&apos;</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="47" relname="span"> I am surprised that
Steve Fuller has gone such a long way in organising his conference without
consulting the SSK people involved at first hand;</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="40" relname="span"> it is curious that he
has consulted the scientists.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="41" relname="span">  He seems to have bought the idea of the
relationship between SSK and the natural sciences that, some, natural
scientists are trying to sell.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="42" relname="span">  We have, on the one hand, people who have
made the study of the social relations of science a lifetime project, and
on th e other hand, those who feel they should pronounce on the matter
without reading the literature properly or considering what the arguments
really mean.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="interpretation">  This `debate&apos; is conducted at the level of slogans.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="46" relname="span">  It can
do nothing but harm to SSK to give this ki nd of debate legitimacy. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="44" relname="condition"> If we
ourselves provide the legitimacy</segment>
    <segment id="44" parent="45" relname="span"> we are acting foolishly indeed. </segment>
