        In sum, I am suggesting that if the proposed Durham conference is
to do good not harm,</segment>
    <segment id="26" parent="61" relname="span"> it should turn on cases of science which have been
examined in full-blooded SSK style;</segment>
    <segment id="27" parent="26" relname="enablement"> there are plenty.</segment>
    <segment id="28" parent="61" relname="elaboration">  It would be
fascinating to hear these discussed by `hard-line rs&apos; such as Peter
Atkins. </segment>
    <segment id="29" parent="62" relname="evaluation"> The conference might then do a lot of good in resolving mutual
suspicion and misunderstanding. </segment>
    <segment id="30" parent="62" relname="evaluation"> I would be happy to participate (now that
I have been invited), under these circumstances. </segment>
    <segment id="31" parent="32" relname="condition"> If, on the other hand,
it is a matter of talking generalities,</segment>
    <segment id="32" parent="63" relname="span"> I believe the conference should
not go ahead.</segment>
